content.text:
Below is a **step‑by‑step tutorial** on building a tiny web‑scraper that pulls the headline list from Hacker News (`https://news.ycombinator.com/news`) using Playwright for JavaScript/TypeScript.  
All the code snippets are ready‑to‑run; copy‑paste them into a fresh project and you’ll have a working scraper in minutes.

---

## 1.  Project bootstrap

```bash
# 1️⃣ Create a new folder and init Node.js
mkdir hn-scraper && cd hn-scraper
npm init -y

# 2️⃣ Install Playwright (and its browsers)
npm i playwright

# 3️⃣ (Optional) install ts-node if you want TypeScript
npm i -D typescript ts-node @types/node
```

> **Tip** – If you prefer JavaScript, skip the TypeScript step and write plain `.js` files.

---

## 2.  Basic Playwright script (JavaScript)

Create `scrape.js`:

```js
// scrape.js
const { chromium } = require('playwright');

(async () => {
  // ① Launch a headless browser
  const browser = await chromium.launch();
  const page = await browser.newPage();

  // ② Navigate to the page you want to scrape
  await page.goto('https://news.ycombinator.com/news');

  // ③ Grab all the rows that contain a story
  // Each story is inside a <tr class="athing"> element
  const rows = await page.$$('tr.athing');

  // ④ Extract title and URL for each story
  const stories = await Promise.all(rows.map(async (row) => {
    // The title is inside a <a class="storylink">
    const titleHandle = await row.$('td.title > a.storylink');
    const title = await titleHandle.innerText();
    const url   = await titleHandle.getAttribute('href');

    return { title, url };
  }));

  // ⑤ Print the results
  console.log('Hacker News Headlines:');
  stories.forEach((s, i) => {
    console.log(`${i + 1}. ${s.title}`);
    console.log(`   → ${s.url}`);
  });

  // ⑥ Clean up
  await browser.close();
})();
```

Run it:

```bash
node scrape.js
```

You should see the current top stories printed to the console.

---

## 3.  Adding a little polish (async/await helpers)

If you like a cleaner API, wrap the scraping logic into a reusable function:

```js
// helpers.js
const { chromium } = require('playwright');

async function scrapeHackerNews() {
  const browser = await chromium.launch();
  const page = await browser.newPage();
  await page.goto('https://news.ycombinator.com/news');

  const stories = await page.$$eval('tr.athing', rows => {
    return rows.map(row => {
      const titleEl = row.querySelector('td.title > a.storylink');
      return {
        title: titleEl.textContent.trim(),
        url: titleEl.href,
      };
    });
  });

  await browser.close();
  return stories;
}

module.exports = { scrapeHackerNews };
```

And a small runner:

```js
// run.js
const { scrapeHackerNews } = require('./helpers');

(async () => {
  const stories = await scrapeHackerNews();
  stories.forEach((s, i) => {
    console.log(`${i + 1}. ${s.title}\n   → ${s.url}`);
  });
})();
```

Run:

```bash
node run.js
```

---

## 4.  Running in **TypeScript** (optional)

If you prefer type safety, create `scrape.ts`:

```ts
import { chromium } from 'playwright';

interface Story {
  title: string;
  url: string;
}

(async () => {
  const browser = await chromium.launch();
  const page = await browser.newPage();

  await page.goto('https://news.ycombinator.com/news');

  const stories: Story[] = await page.$$eval('tr.athing', rows =>
    rows.map(row => {
      const titleEl = row.querySelector('td.title > a.storylink') as HTMLAnchorElement;
      return {
        title: titleEl.textContent!.trim(),
        url: titleEl.href,
      };
    })
  );

  console.log('Hacker News Headlines:');
  stories.forEach((s, i) => {
    console.log(`${i + 1}. ${s.title}`);
    console.log(`   → ${s.url}`);
  });

  await browser.close();
})();
```

Compile & run:

```bash
npx ts-node scrape.ts
```

---

## 5.  Common pitfalls & quick fixes

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
|---------|-------|-----|
| **`Error: Protocol error (Target.setAutoAttach) …`** | Browser not launched correctly (e.g., `headless: false` missing when using Docker) | Add `headless: true/false` to `chromium.launch()` or set `PLAYWRIGHT_BROWSERS_PATH` accordingly. |
| **`Cannot find module 'playwright'`** | Node modules not installed in the current dir | Run `npm install` in the project folder. |
| **Selectors returning empty arrays** | Page layout changed or wrong selector | Inspect the page with DevTools, confirm `<tr class="athing">` still exists. Update selector accordingly. |
| **Slow or flaky runs** | Network issues or anti‑scraping countermeasures | Add `await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle')` after `goto`, or add a small delay with `page.waitForTimeout(500)`. |

---

## 6.  Extending the scraper

* **Pagination** – `https://news.ycombinator.com/news?p=2` for page 2.  
  Add a loop that increments the `p` query param.

* **Download article content** – After collecting URLs, launch a new page for each URL, extract `<article>` or `<p>` tags.

* **Persist data** – Write the array to a JSON file:

  ```js
  const fs = require('fs');
  fs.writeFileSync('hn-headlines.json', JSON.stringify(stories, null, 2));
  ```

* **Headless CI** – When running on CI, make sure the Playwright browsers are installed:

  ```bash
  npx playwright install --with-deps
  ```

---

## 7.  Final words

- **Playwright** gives you powerful, cross‑browser automation with a simple API.  
- The code above demonstrates the core pattern: launch → navigate → evaluate → close.  
- Keep your selectors **specific** and **stable**; the Hacker News layout is simple, but any change will break the scraper.  
- For production‑grade scrapers, add error handling, rate‑limiting, and optional headless mode toggles.

Happy scraping! 🚀
